    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix scheduling priority inversion in security mode command handling\n\n### Summary\nThere is a scheduling priority inversion where lower-priority traffic is served before higher-priority downstream of function handle_security_mode_command. Security Mode Complete messages are being sent with the same priority as regular NAS messages, potentially causing delays in the security setup process.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair2/COMMON/rrc_messages_def.h`: Added new high-priority message type NAS_UPLINK_DATA_REQ_HIGH_PRIORITY\n- `openair2/COMMON/rrc_messages_types.h`: Added corresponding macro definition\n- `openair3/NAS/NR_UE/nr_nas_msg.c`: Modified send_nas_uplink_data_req to detect security-related messages and send them with higher priority\n\n### Reproduction\nWhen a UE receives a Security Mode Command from the network, it should respond with a Security Mode Complete message immediately. However, due to the priority inversion, other lower-priority NAS messages may be processed first, causing delays in the security setup procedure. This can be observed as increased latency in the authentication and security activation phase during initial registration.\n\nThe issue manifests when:\n1. UE receives Security Mode Command (message type 0x5e)\n2. UE generates Security Mode Complete response\n3. Response is queued with regular priority instead of high priority\n4. Other NAS messages with higher priority are processed first\n5. Security setup is delayed, potentially causing registration timeouts\n\nThis fix ensures that Security Mode Complete and Security Mode Reject messages are sent with higher priority, resolving the scheduling inversion.\n"
}